    "1": {
      "text": "William Molyneux was born in Dublin, studied in Trinity College Dublin (TCD), and was a founding member of the Dublin Philosophical Society (DPS), Ireland's counterpart to the Royal Society in London",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "2": {
      "text": "For these reasons, the intellectual environment in Dublin and Ireland is where the effects of Molyneux's famous question would have been most immediately and directly felt",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "3": {
      "text": "For the most part, Irish thinkers in the seventeenth and eighteenth centuries answered 'no' to Molyneux's question of whether a blind man made to see could distinguish, by sight alone, between a cube and a sphere",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "4": {
      "text": "This is most likely due to the influence of Locke's Essay (1975: II.ix.viii), which was part of the curriculum at TCD from an early stage after being recommended to the provost by Molyneux himself",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "5": {
      "text": "The thinkers we discuss, in what follows, all agree that a blind man could not conceive of light or colours or represent to himself visual ideas more generally",
      "label": "claim"
